1 Task 1: Data Source

I selected a 994 subjects sample of the **Hispanic Health and Nutrition Examination Survey“** HHANES conducted by the National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS) from 1982 to 1984. This data is interesting because it was collected on”the three largest Hispanic subgroups“, Mexican-americans, Cuban-americans, and Puerto Ricans.

The data is accessible to the public, and it is provided in several files that need to be merged. I selected to use the sections: “Diabetes and OGTT Data, Ages 20-74 years, 6506” and “Dietary Practices, Food Frequency and Total Nutrient Intake, 6525”. In addition the National Center for Health Statistics provids with SAS code to appropriately inport the data which is in .txt format. Thus, I first imported the data using the SAS files provided by NCHS, and exported a SAS file. Secondly, I imported the SAS files into R using the “haven” package, and continued to merge and create a CSV file.

5 Task 5: My Subjects

The data holds information for 994 subjects from three specific geographic areas and categorized in three groups: Mexican-Americans (from five southwestern states), Cuban-Americans (from Dade county, Fl) and Puerto Ricans (from New York City). Subjects in this sample are 20-74 years old, and mean age 41.6 years.

6 Task 6: My Variables

The 12 variables included in this data set are:

names(HHANES_s)
 [1] "SEQN"                "age"                 "sex"                
 [4] "national.origin"     "incomegroup"         "plasma.glucose"     
 [7] "fruit"               "vegetables"          "sodas"              
[10] "sugar"               "cake.cookies"        "High.plasma.glucose"
[13] "DM_self_reported"

  1. SEQN, is the subject’s identification code.

  2. plasma.glucose is a quantitative variable with values for plasma glucose measured in Mg/Dl.

  3. High.plasma.glucose is a binary variable, calculated by assinging a number 1 if plasma glucose was above 110 Mg/Dl and 0 for plasma glucose below 110 Mg/Dl.

  4. age, is the age of individual at the time of the interview measured in years.

  5. National.origin, is the subject’s national origin according to place of birth, or his/her ancestry.

  6. ‘insurance’, is a binary variable which provides information on whether the person was covered by any health insurance plan at the time of the survey.

  7. incomegroup, is a a multi-categorical variable that answers to the following question: “Of those income groups, which best represents the total combined family income during the past 12 months?” There are 27 categories in $1000 increments. starting at less than 1000 to $50,000 and over,

  8. DM_self_reported, is a binary variable, that answers to the question “Do you have diabetes?” It is then self-reported status of diabetes.

The following variables are multicategorical variable, from section L “food group categories and reported consumption”. The categories in theses variables are: ‘water’|Multi-categorical | 0=never, 1=Daily, 2=Weekly, 7=Less than onces a week, 8=Blank but applicable, 9=unknown

  1. cake.cookies, is how often the individual eats cake, cookies and the likes.

  2. Sodas, is how often the individual drinks sodas.

  3. Sugar, is how oftenthe individual uses sugar.

  4. Vegeables, is how often the individual eats any vegetables.

  5. fruit, is how often the individual eats any fruit.
